        <h3 data-uuid="b81e5c4c8ea24997ad3daba5170437a1">Northern Resources</h3>
        <p data-uuid="894b1d323f4d421da1c611dd6b8123a4">Numbers tell an important story about the Civil War. Consider the North’s advantages. It could draw soldiers and workers from a population of 22 million. The South had only 5.5 million people to draw from. One of the greatest advantages in the North was the region’s network of roads, canals, and railroads. Some 22,000 miles of railroad track could move soldiers and supplies throughout the North. The South had only about 9,000 miles of track.</p>
        <p data-uuid="5250269e0951488bac7fe4559e8d9eed">In the North, the Civil War stimulated economic growth. To supply the military, the production of coal, iron, wheat, and wool increased. Also, the export of corn, wheat, beef, and pork to Europe doubled. In the South, the export of resources decreased because of the Union blockade.</p>
        <p data-uuid="e1a5f79df0094b61b337daf607d32927"> Finally, the Union had money. It had a more developed economy, banking system, and a currency called greenbacks. The South had to start printing its own Confederate dollars. Some states printed their own money, too. This led to financial chaos.<br />
        </p>
